"""
MKT Context — Leviticus chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-leviticus-19-21.py
ch19 (37 verses): Holiness Code ethical core — love-neighbor, gleaning, honest weights,
                   treatment of foreigners, mixed categories (sha'atnez, forbidden mixtures)
ch20 (27 verses): Penalties — Molech sacrifice, mediums, sexual sins; holiness refrain
ch21 (24 verses): Priestly holiness code — mourning restrictions, marriage standards, physical defects
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

new_entries = {
"19": {
"1": "<p>The address shifts from Moses alone to <b>kol adat benei Yisrael</b> — the entire congregation of the people of Israel. This is one of the few times in Leviticus that the audience is the full assembly rather than just Moses or the priests. The Holiness Code (chs. 17-26) addresses all Israel as a priestly people; holiness is not the exclusive concern of the Levitical caste but the calling of the entire covenant community.</p>",
"2": "<p><b>Qedoshim tihyu ki qadosh ani YHWH eloheichem</b>: you shall be holy, for I YHWH your God am holy. The theological foundation of the entire Holiness Code. Holiness is grounded in divine nature, not in human achievement: Israel is to be holy because YHWH is holy. The imitation-of-God ethic (<em>imitatio Dei</em>) that underlies Leviticus 19 — treating others as YHWH treats Israel — is one of the most sophisticated ethical frameworks in the ancient world. The declaration precedes any specific command: the imperative arises from the indicative of divine character.</p>",
"3": "<p><b>Ish imo veavio tirau</b>: each person shall fear (<em>yira</em>) his mother and his father. The reversal of the usual order (father-mother) is deliberate: mother is listed first, perhaps to balance the patriarchal cultural default. <em>Yira</em> (reverence, fear) rather than <em>ahav</em> (love) is used for parents — parental reverence encompasses respect, obedience, and maintenance. The conjunction of parent-fear and Sabbath-keeping in the same verse links domestic ethics and liturgical practice as equally important expressions of holiness.</p>",
"4": "<p><b>Al tifnu el-haelilim</b>: do not turn to idols (<em>elilim</em> = worthless nothings). The prohibition on idols and cast images at the opening of the practical holiness commands mirrors the Decalogue. The Holiness Code presupposes the Decalogue framework: its ethical content is the Decalogue applied across all domains of social life.</p>",
"5": "<p><b>Vechi tizbechu zevach shelamim l-YHWH</b>: when you sacrifice a peace offering (<em>shelamim</em>) to YHWH. The peace offering regulations here (vv. 5-8) parallel those of ch. 7: the offering must be eaten within two days; eating on the third day disqualifies the offering as piggul (<em>pigul</em> = desecration). The time-limit preserves the integrity of the communion meal: the sacred food must be consumed while still fresh, not stored as private provision. The two-day rule makes the peace offering a genuinely communal, time-bounded act of worship.</p>",
"6": "<p><b>Beyom zivchachem ye'achel uvamachorat</b>: it shall be eaten on the day of sacrifice and on the next day. The two-day eating window for the peace offering reflects both practical food-safety concerns (in a pre-refrigeration culture) and theological integrity: the meal is an act of worship, not a stockpile. The parallel in 7:15-18 establishes this as standard Levitical law.</p>",
"7": "<p><b>Ve-im he'achol ye'achel bayom hashlishi piggul hu</b>: if it is eaten at all on the third day, it is piggul (desecrated/loathsome). <em>Piggul</em> (an Akkadian loanword suggesting something offensive or stinking) describes food that has become ritually unfit — not by external contamination but by improper time of consumption. The third-day disqualification renders the entire offering retroactively invalid and the eater bears guilt (<em>avon</em>).</p>",
"8": "<p><b>Veoklav avono yissa ki et-qodesh YHWH chillel</b>: the one who eats it shall bear his iniquity, for he has profaned the holy thing of YHWH. <em>Chillel</em> (to profane, make common) is the opposite of <em>qiddesh</em> (to sanctify, make holy) — the same root as <em>chol</em> (ordinary, secular). Treating sacred food as ordinary by eating it too late collapses the distinction between holy and common that is fundamental to Levitical theology.</p>",
"9": "<p><b>Uvekutzrachem et-qetzir artzechem lo techaleh peat sadecha liqtzor</b>: when you reap the harvest of your land, you shall not reap to the edge (<em>peat</em>) of your field. The gleaning laws (vv. 9-10) are the Holiness Code's most direct expression of economic ethics. <em>Peat</em> (corner, edge) and <em>laqat</em> (to glean, pick up fallen grain) define the portions intentionally left for the poor. Agricultural abundance comes with a built-in redistribution mechanism: the edges of the field and the dropped grain belong to the poor and the stranger by divine command. Ruth 2 is the narrative embodiment of this law.</p>",
"10": "<p><b>Vecharmelcha lo teolel uferaten karmecha lo telaqqet laani velagen tetov otam</b>: you shall not strip your vineyard bare (<em>teolel</em> = to glean thoroughly, pick over), and you shall not gather the fallen grapes (<em>peret</em>) — leave them for the poor and the sojourner. The vineyard parallel to the grain-field: both have an intentional margin of incompletion. The gleaning laws institutionalize generosity by making it a matter of divine command rather than voluntary charity. The poor have a right to the margins; the owner must actively restrain from full extraction.</p>",
"11": "<p><b>Lo tignovu velo techachedu velo teshaqru ish bamito</b>: you shall not steal (<em>ganav</em>), deal falsely (<em>kachash</em>), or lie to one another. The triplet of theft, deception, and lying covers the main modes of dishonest social interaction. <em>Kachash</em> (to deny, deal falsely, deceive by understatement) and <em>shaqar</em> (to lie) together cover both implicit and explicit dishonesty. The specific construction <em>ish bamito</em> (a man toward his fellow/companion) places these prohibitions in the context of neighbor-relationships — the same context as the love-neighbor command of v18.</p>",
"12": "<p><b>Velo tishavu bishmi lashaqer</b>: you shall not swear falsely by my name. The false oath invokes the divine name to guarantee a lie — a double violation: dishonesty plus misuse of the divine name (cf. the third commandment, Exod 20:7). <em>Challel et shem elohecha</em> (you would profane the name of your God) — false oaths are not merely contractual fraud but theological profanation. The name of YHWH cannot be used as an instrument of deception without damaging the relationship between the community and its God.</p>",
"13": "<p><b>Lo taashoq et-reecha velo tigzol</b>: you shall not oppress (<em>ashaq</em>) your neighbor or rob (<em>gazal</em>) him. <em>Ashaq</em> (to oppress, exploit, extort) covers economic coercion — using power to extract from those who are vulnerable. The wages of a hired worker must not be held overnight — <em>lo-talin peulat sachir itecha ad-boqer</em>. The same day-wage rule appears in Deut 24:15. ANE labor contracts often included provisions about timely payment, but here it is a divine command. The vulnerability of the day laborer — who depends on same-day wages for that evening's food — means delayed payment is effectively theft.</p>",
"14": "<p><b>Lo teqallel cheresh velifnei iver lo titen michshol</b>: you shall not curse the deaf (<em>cheresh</em>), and before the blind (<em>iver</em>) you shall not put a stumbling block. The deaf person cannot hear the curse; the blind cannot see the obstacle placed before them — they are by definition unable to defend themselves. The prohibition of exploiting vulnerability is extended to situations where the victim cannot even perceive the offense. <em>Veyarerta mielohecha</em>: you shall fear (<em>yare</em>) your God — the divine omniscience supplies what human accountability lacks; YHWH sees even what the victim cannot.</p>",
"15": "<p><b>Lo ta'asu avel bamishpat</b>: you shall not do injustice (<em>avel</em>) in judgment (<em>mishpat</em>). The prohibition of partiality in legal proceedings — not favoring the poor (dal) or being partial to the great (<em>gadol</em>). The symmetric prohibition against both economic-class favoritism (favoring the poor against the rich) and power-class favoritism (favoring the wealthy/influential) establishes that justice is blind to social status. <em>Betzedek tishpot amitecha</em>: in righteousness you shall judge your fellow. The positive formulation completes the negative: not just avoiding injustice but actively practicing righteousness.</p>",
"16": "<p><b>Lo telech rachil baamecha</b>: you shall not go about (<em>halak</em>) as a slanderer (<em>rachil</em>) among your people. <em>Rachil</em> (slanderer, gossip, from the same root as merchant/trader) suggests someone who traffics in damaging information about others. <em>Lo taamod al dam reecha</em>: you shall not stand against the blood of your neighbor — failing to act when someone's life is at stake. The juxtaposition of slander (active harm through speech) with failure to rescue (passive harm through silence) covers both the misuse and the withholding of speech in neighbor relationships.</p>",
"17": "<p><b>Lo tisna et-achicha bilvavecha</b>: you shall not hate your brother in your heart. The internalization of the ethical command is significant: the prohibition extends beyond external action to interior attitude. <em>Bilvavecha</em> (in your heart) makes hidden contempt as prohibited as open hostility. <em>Hocheach tochiach et-amitecha</em>: you shall certainly rebuke (<em>hocheach tochiach</em>, infinitive absolute for emphasis) your neighbor. Active rebuke is commanded as the alternative to silent resentment — confronting a wrong is more loving than nursing a grievance. <em>Velo tisa alav chet</em>: you shall not bear sin because of him — failing to rebuke makes the bystander complicit in the sin.</p>",
"18": "<p><b>Lo tiqom velo-titor et-benei ammecha veahavta lereiacha kamocha ani YHWH</b>: you shall not take vengeance or bear a grudge (<em>nator</em> = to keep, maintain, preserve — a grudge is a grievance preserved) against the sons of your people, but you shall love (<em>ahav</em>) your neighbor (<em>rea</em>) as yourself. The command to love neighbor is the climax of the preceding sequence (vv. 11-17). <em>Rea</em> (neighbor, fellow, companion) in context covers the full range of social relationships within the community. The self-referential standard (<em>kamocha</em> = as yourself) grounds the command in universal human self-interest: the measure of what you owe your neighbor is what you know you need yourself. The closing <em>ani YHWH</em> (I am YHWH) supplies both authority and motivation: the covenant God who loves Israel commands Israel to extend that love laterally.</p>",
"19": "<p><b>Huqqotai tishmorunu</b>: you shall keep my statutes. The section on forbidden mixtures (<em>kilayim</em>) addresses: (1) breeding livestock with different species; (2) sowing a field with two kinds of seed (<em>sha'atnez</em> applies here); (3) wearing a garment woven from two materials (<em>sha'atnez</em> = mixed fiber cloth, wool-and-linen). The <em>kilayim</em> (mixtures, from <em>kele</em> = to restrain, hold back) prohibitions preserve divinely established categories. The same principle underlying the clean/unclean distinctions — categories must not be collapsed — governs the kilayim rules: the integrity of created kinds reflects the integrity of the Creator's order.</p>",
"20": "<p><b>Ve-ish ki yishkav et-isha shikhvat-zera</b>: when a man lies with a woman and there is intercourse. This case involves a slave woman betrothed to another man but not yet redeemed or granted freedom. The case sits between fully free and fully slave, creating a liminal legal status that requires a specific ruling. Because she is not fully free, the death penalty for adultery does not apply; instead a <em>biqqoret</em> (investigation, inquiry, or scourging — the term is debated) is required, and a guilt offering (<em>asham</em>) is brought.</p>",
"21": "<p><b>Vehevi et-ashamo l-YHWH</b>: he shall bring his guilt offering (<em>asham</em>) to YHWH. The guilt offering in this case provides atonement for the violation of the betrothed slave woman's protected status. The requirement of a formal atonement ritual for what might otherwise be treated as a purely civil matter demonstrates that sexual ethics in the Holiness Code has a theological dimension: violations against persons are violations against YHWH's covenant order.</p>",
"22": "<p><b>Vechipper alav hakkohen biil ha-asham lifnei YHWH al-chatato asher chata venislach lo me-chatato asher chata</b>: the priest shall make atonement for him before YHWH, and he shall be forgiven for the sin he has committed. The atonement-and-forgiveness formula here — identical to the standard sin/guilt offering formula — applies even in the slave-woman case. No violation is beyond the reach of the atonement system, but none is beneath requiring it either.</p>",
"23": "<p><b>Veki tavo-u el-haaretz untemtem kol-etz maakal vaarltem orlato et-piryo</b>: when you enter the land and plant any fruit tree, you shall treat its fruit as forbidden (<em>orlah</em>, literally: uncircumcised). The first three years of fruit are <em>arel</em> (uncircumcised, forbidden) — not to be eaten. <em>Orlah</em> (the foreskin; used metaphorically for what is sealed/restricted) is applied to fruit, connecting the circumcision covenant-mark to agricultural practice. The first-fruits theology requires patient waiting: the tree must establish itself before humans take its fruit. Mishnah Orlah is an entire tractate devoted to the practical application of this law.</p>",
"24": "<p><b>Uvhashanah hareviyit yihyeh kol-piryo qodesh hillulim l-YHWH</b>: in the fourth year all its fruit shall be holy — a jubilation offering (<em>hillulim</em>, from <em>halel</em> = to praise) to YHWH. The fourth-year fruit is entirely dedicated to YHWH as a praise offering — <em>hillulim</em> is a festive, joyful offering. Only in the fifth year may the owner eat the fruit for personal benefit. The delayed-gratification structure (3 years forbidden + 1 year dedicated + 5th year yours) teaches that the land's produce belongs to YHWH first.</p>",
"25": "<p><b>Uvhashanah hachamishit tochelu et-piryo lehosif lachem tevuatah</b>: in the fifth year you may eat its fruit, to increase its yield for you — I am YHWH your God. The obedience to the orlah laws increases the tree's yield (<em>lehosif... tevuatah</em>): the theological principle that covenant obedience produces abundance is applied even to horticultural practice. The closing <em>ani YHWH eloheichem</em> connects the agricultural law to covenant identity.</p>",
"26": "<p><b>Lo tochelu al-hadam</b>: you shall not eat any flesh with the blood (<em>al-hadam</em>). The prohibition on blood-eating echoes Lev 17:10-14 and connects to the ANE divination practice of eating flesh with blood in magical/cultic contexts. The following prohibitions on divination (<em>nachash</em>) and augury (<em>anan</em>) are in the same cluster — the blood-eating, divination, and augury prohibitions address practices that sought to access spiritual power outside the covenant framework.</p>",
"27": "<p><b>Lo taqifu peat roshechem velo tashchit et-peat zeqanecha</b>: you shall not round off the hair on your temples (<em>peat rosh</em>) or mar the edges of your beard. The hair-cutting prohibition addresses mourning practices common in Canaanite religion — shaving specific areas of the head and beard was associated with pagan rituals for the dead. The prohibition distinguishes Israelite mourning from syncretistic practices (cf. Deut 14:1). The peat rosh regulations may also be connected to clan-identification markings.</p>",
"28": "<p><b>Veseret lanefesh lo titenu bivesarchem uchtovt qaqqa lo titenu bachem</b>: you shall not make any cuts (<em>seret</em>) on your body for the dead, or tattoo yourselves (<em>ketovot qa'aqa</em>) — I am YHWH. Both cutting for the dead (a mourning rite common in Baal worship; cf. 1 Kgs 18:28) and tattooing (permanent body marking) are prohibited as pagan practices that mark the body as belonging to another deity or that participate in death-cult rituals. <em>Ani YHWH</em> closes the prohibition: the body belongs to YHWH, not to the death-powers of surrounding religion.</p>",
"29": "<p><b>Al techallel et-bitcha lehaznotah</b>: do not degrade your daughter by making her a prostitute (<em>zanah</em>). The warning against cult prostitution (or economic exploitation of daughters through prostitution) — <em>velo-tizne haaretz umalah haaretz zimmah</em> (lest the land become full of <em>zimmah</em>, a term for sexual wickedness/shameful scheming). The land itself is conceived as a moral participant: sexual sin fills the land with corruption in the same way that blood guilt does (Num 35:33).</p>",
"30": "<p><b>Et-shabbetotai tishmoru umiqdashi tirau</b>: you shall keep my Sabbaths and reverence my sanctuary — the refrain that brackets the Holiness Code (cf. 26:2). The Sabbath and sanctuary commands appear again here in the middle of the chapter's ethical content, reminding that the social ethics of ch. 19 cannot be separated from the liturgical framework: ethical behavior and worship belong together.</p>",
"31": "<p><b>Al tifnu el-haoboth veal haydeonim al-tevaqshu letomah bahem</b>: do not turn to mediums (<em>ovoth</em>) or wizards/necromancers (<em>yideoni</em>). <em>Ov</em> (a medium, one who consults the dead — possibly referring to the pit-spirit through which necromancers communicated) and <em>yideoni</em> (a knowing one, a familiar spirit) cover the main forms of occult consultation in the ANE. The prohibition is grounded positively in covenant relationship: seeking knowledge from the dead is a rejection of YHWH as the source of guidance and knowledge.</p>",
"32": "<p><b>Mipnei seivah taqum vehadarta penei zaqen veyarata meelohecha</b>: you shall stand (<em>taqum</em>) before the gray-haired and honor the face of the aged, and you shall fear your God. The elderly are owed honor not because of individual achievement but because of age itself — a principle that cuts against both meritocracy and youth-culture. The connection between honoring elders and fearing God (<em>veyarata meelohecha</em>) grounds intergenerational respect in the same theological place as respect for the vulnerable: YHWH sees what human status-systems ignore.</p>",
"33": "<p><b>Vechi yagur itecha ger beartzechem lo tonub</b>: when a stranger (<em>ger</em>) sojourns with you in your land, you shall not wrong (<em>onah</em>) him. <em>Ger</em> (sojourner, resident alien — not a temporary visitor but a long-term resident without native-born rights) receives specific legal protection in the Holiness Code. <em>Onah</em> (to wrong, oppress, afflict — the same root as <em>ana</em> in 19:13) covers economic, social, and legal exploitation of resident foreigners.</p>",
"34": "<p><b>Keozerach mikem yihyeh lachem hager hagor itchem veahavta lo kamocha ki gerim heyitem beeretz mitzraim</b>: the stranger who sojourns with you shall be to you as the native among you, and you shall love him as yourself, for you were strangers in the land of Egypt. The extension of the love-neighbor command (v18) to the <em>ger</em> is among the most remarkable commands in Leviticus. The motivation is empathetic-historical: Israel's own experience as foreigners (<em>gerim</em>) in Egypt is the ground for treating foreigners well. The Exodus memory is the ethical engine that drives neighbor-extension.</p>",
"35": "<p><b>Lo ta'asu avel bamishpat bammidah bammishqal uvammeshura</b>: you shall not do injustice in judgment, in measures of length (<em>midah</em>), in weight (<em>mishqal</em>), or in quantity (<em>meshurah</em>). The prohibition on false weights and measures covers three dimensions of commercial measurement. The ANE merchant carried two sets of weights — heavier for buying, lighter for selling — a practice explicitly condemned here and in Amos 8:5, Micah 6:11, Proverbs 11:1.</p>",
"36": "<p><b>Mozanei tzedeq avnei tzedeq eifat tzedeq vehin tzedeq yihyeh lachem</b>: just balances (<em>mozanei tzedeq</em>), just weights (<em>avnei tzedeq</em>), a just ephah (<em>eifat tzedeq</em>), and a just hin (<em>hin tzedeq</em>) you shall have. <em>Tzedeq</em> (righteousness, justice, right) applied to commercial instruments: the scales, stones, and measures must themselves be characterized by justice. The context is the Exodus: <em>ani YHWH eloheichem asher hotzeiti etchem meeretz mitzraim</em> (I am YHWH your God who brought you out of Egypt) — the God who redeemed Israel with exact precision demands exact precision in commercial dealings.</p>",
"37": "<p><b>Ushmartem et kol-chuqotai veet-kol-mishpatai vaasitem otam ani YHWH</b>: you shall observe all my statutes and all my rules and do them — I am YHWH. The closing verse of the Holiness Code's practical ethics section provides the same double formula (keep + do) that opens ch. 19 (v3: <em>tishmoru... veshabbetotai</em>). The bracket of Sabbath/sanctuary at vv. 3 and 30, combined with the opening (v2) and closing (v37) holiness-formula, gives ch. 19 a carefully structured literary shape around the central love-neighbor command of v18.</p>"
},
"20": {
"1": "<p>The penalty chapter (ch. 20) is the enforcement counterpart to the prohibition chapter (ch. 18). Where ch. 18 lists the forbidden sexual relations and practices, ch. 20 assigns specific penalties. The chapter is addressed again to <b>benei Yisrael</b> — the full community, not just the priests.</p>",
"2": "<p><b>Ish ish mibenei Yisrael umin-hager hagar beYisrael asher yiten mizaro laMolech mot yumat</b>: any Israelite or sojourner in Israel who gives his children to Molech (<em>laMolech</em>) shall be put to death. <em>Molech</em> is a deity associated with child sacrifice — the name may derive from <em>melek</em> (king) or from the offering term <em>molech/mulk</em> (a type of vow-sacrifice in Punic inscriptions). The <em>tofet</em> (furnace/hearth) in the Hinnom Valley outside Jerusalem (Jer 7:31) was the site of Molech-child sacrifice. The stoning penalty for Molech worship is carried out by <em>am haaretz</em> (the people of the land) — communal enforcement rather than judicial execution alone.</p>",
"3": "<p><b>Va-ani etten et-panai ba-ish hahu vehichratti oto miqqerev ammo</b>: and I will set my face against that man and cut him off (<em>karet</em>) from among his people. The divine face-setting against Molech worshipers introduces both human penalty (stoning) and divine penalty (karet = being cut off). <em>Karet</em> (cutting off) is the distinctive Levitical divine penalty — distinct from human-executed punishment, it describes premature death or exclusion from covenant community at the divine level. Giving children to Molech is specifically described as defiling YHWH's sanctuary and profaning his holy name — the theological gravity matches the penalty's severity.</p>",
"4": "<p><b>Ve-im haalem yaaleimu am haaretz et-eineihem min-ha-ish hahu</b>: if the people of the land at all close their eyes (<em>haalem yaaleimu</em>, an emphatic infinitive absolute) to that man. Social complicity — willful ignorance of a covenant violation — is itself punishable. The community that fails to act against Molech worship shares in its guilt. The communal enforcement mechanism built into the Holiness Code makes every Israelite a stakeholder in covenant maintenance.</p>",
"5": "<p><b>Vesamti ani et-panai ba-ish hahu uvemishpachto vehichratti oto</b>: I myself will set my face against that man and his family and cut him off. The divine penalty extends to the family — not because relatives are automatically guilty but because participation in Molech worship was typically a family affair, and the community of the household shares in its head's apostasy.</p>",
"6": "<p><b>Vehanefesh asher tifneh el-haoboth veel-hayideonim liznot achareihem</b>: the person who turns to mediums (<em>ovoth</em>) and necromancers (<em>yideonim</em>) to prostitute himself by following them. The language of spiritual prostitution (<em>liznot</em>) connects occult consultation with idolatry — both are covenant infidelity. The penalty is karet — divine cutting off.</p>",
"7": "<p><b>Vehitqaddashtem vihyitem qedoshim ki ani YHWH eloheichem</b>: consecrate yourselves and be holy, for I am YHWH your God. The holiness refrain (cf. 19:2) appears here at the center of the penalty chapter, reminding that the penalties serve a constructive purpose: they protect the holiness of the community. The penalties are not merely punitive but purgative — removing the corruption that threatens the integrity of the covenant people.</p>",
"8": "<p><b>Ushmartem et-chuqqotai vaasitem otam ani YHWH meqaddishchem</b>: keep my statutes and do them — I am YHWH who sanctifies you (<em>meqaddishchem</em>). YHWH is the agent of Israel's sanctification: Israel does not make itself holy through observance but is made holy by YHWH. The keeping of statutes is the human response to divine sanctification, not its cause.</p>",
"9": "<p><b>Ki-ish ish asher yeqallel et-aviv veet-immo mot yumat</b>: anyone who curses his father or mother shall be put to death. The capital penalty for cursing parents places parental honor at the level of covenant seriousness — consistent with the fifth commandment's position in the Decalogue. <em>Aviv veimmo qillel</em>: he has cursed his father and his mother — his blood is upon him (<em>damo bo</em>). The self-responsibility formula (<em>damo bo</em>) recurs throughout the penalty chapter, indicating that the condemned person bears the moral weight of their own execution.</p>",
"10": "<p><b>Veish asher yinaf et-eshet ish asher yinaf et-eshet reehub</b>: a man who commits adultery with the wife of his fellow. Both the adulterer and the adulteress shall be put to death. The symmetry of the penalty — both parties equally liable — reflects a significant level of gender equity in the judicial framework compared to some ANE law codes that punished only the woman. The equal penalty affirms that both parties acted as moral agents and both bear equal responsibility.</p>",
"11": "<p><b>Veish asher yishkav et-eshet aviv</b>: the man who lies with his father's wife. This covers both the man and the woman: both shall be put to death, their blood is upon them. The penalty section (vv. 10-21) applies capital punishment or karet to the forbidden relations listed in ch. 18, working through the same categories: adultery (v10), father's wife (v11), daughter-in-law (v12), male homosexual intercourse (v13), and so on.</p>",
"12": "<p><b>Veish asher yishkav et-khalato</b>: a man who lies with his daughter-in-law — both shall be put to death. <em>Tevel</em> (confusion, perversion) is the term for this violation — the same word used in Lev 18:23 for bestiality. The term reflects the Levitical categorization: these acts mix what should be kept distinct (parent/child-in-law roles; human/animal categories).</p>",
"13": "<p><b>Ve-ish asher yishkav et-zachar mishkevei isha</b>: a man who lies with a male as with a woman — both have committed an abomination (<em>to'evah</em>). The same term (<em>to'evah</em>) and the same capital penalty as in 18:22. The context of the penalty chapter's systematic treatment of all forbidden relations shows this is not a marginal concern in the Holiness Code but is treated as seriously as adultery and incest.</p>",
"14": "<p><b>Veish asher yiqqach et-isha veet-imma zimmah hi</b>: a man who takes a woman and her mother — it is depravity (<em>zimmah</em>). All three shall be burned (<em>basesh yisrefu</em>) — the distinctive penalty of burning (rather than stoning) is reserved for the most egregious cases (cf. Lev 21:9 for a priest's daughter). The severity of the penalty reflects the severity of the violation: multiple kinship bonds collapsed simultaneously.</p>",
"15": "<p><b>Veish asher yitten shekhavto bivehemah</b>: a man who lies with an animal shall be put to death, and you shall kill the animal as well. The animal's execution (despite its lack of moral agency) serves to remove the instrument of the violation from the community — a practice paralleled in the case of a goring ox (Exod 21:28-29). The animal is a <em>davar nevelah</em> (something unclean); its removal prevents any further use of it that would perpetuate the defilement.</p>",
"16": "<p><b>Ve-isha asher tiqrav el kol-behemah lerivatah otah</b>: and a woman who approaches any animal to lie with it — you shall kill the woman and the animal. The equal treatment of male and female in the bestiality penalties is consistent with the chapter's pattern of bilateral moral accountability.</p>",
"17": "<p><b>Veish asher yiqqach et-achoto bat-aviv o vat-immo</b>: a man who takes his sister — daughter of his father or daughter of his mother. The penalty is karet rather than execution, suggesting a different level of severity even within the category of forbidden unions. <em>Chesed hu</em> (it is a disgrace/shame) — <em>chesed</em> in this unusual sense means shameful lovingkindness (the word's positive meaning inverted) — some render it reproach or disgrace.</p>",
"18": "<p><b>Veish asher yishkav et-isha davah</b>: a man who lies with a woman during her menstrual impurity — both shall be cut off (<em>nikretu</em>) from among their people. The mutual karet penalty for deliberate violation of the niddah restriction is lighter than execution but still serious. The bilateral penalty again emphasizes mutual moral agency.</p>",
"19": "<p><b>Veervet achat imecha veervet achat avicha lo tegalleh</b>: you shall not uncover the nakedness of your mother's sister or your father's sister — it would uncover one's own flesh (<em>sheer</em>). The karet penalty applies. The aunt relationships involve not just the direct kin but the extension of the kin-network into which one is embedded.</p>",
"20": "<p><b>Veish asher yishkav et-dodato</b>: a man who lies with his uncle's wife. This case does not receive the execution penalty but instead: <em>chataam yis'u</em> (they shall bear their punishment/sin), and they shall die childless (<em>aririn yamuto</em>). The death-without-children penalty is understood as a divine curse rather than a judicial execution — a form of the Holiness Code's awareness that covenant violations bring natural consequences, not only judicial ones.</p>",
"21": "<p><b>Veish asher yiqqach et-eshet achiv niddah hi</b>: a man who takes his brother's wife — it is impurity (<em>niddah</em>). The same consequence: they shall die childless. This is the reverse of the levirate marriage institution (Deut 25:5-10) where marrying a deceased brother's wife was required. The different treatment reflects whether the brother is alive (here: forbidden, treated as adultery) or dead without children (Deut 25: commanded to preserve the family name).</p>",
"22": "<p><b>Ushmartem et-kol-chuqqotai veet-kol-mishpatai vaasitem otam</b>: keep all my statutes and all my rules and do them. The land-vomiting warning reappears: <em>velo taqii etchem haaretz asher ani meivi etchem shamah lashevet ba</em> (so that the land to which I am bringing you to dwell there does not vomit you out). The land is personified as a moral participant that cannot tolerate persistent covenant violation — the same imagery as 18:28.</p>",
"23": "<p><b>Velo telechu bechukot hagoy asher anochi meshalleach mipeneichem</b>: you shall not walk in the statutes of the nation that I am sending out before you. The Canaanites' expulsion from the land is attributed to their practice of the very offenses listed in the chapter — not ethnic inferiority but covenant-violation resulted in their removal. This theology prevents Israel from claiming special treatment: the same standard applies to them if they commit the same violations.</p>",
"24": "<p><b>Va-omar lachem atem tirbu et-admatam va-ani atenah lachem la-reshet otah eretz zavat chalav udevash</b>: I said to you that you would inherit their land — a land flowing with milk and honey. The promise of the land is grounded in the distinction YHWH made between Israel and the nations: <em>va-avdil etchem min-haamim lihyot li</em> (I have separated you from the peoples to be mine). The separation theology of the Holiness Code serves an election purpose: Israel's distinctiveness is not superiority but vocation — to be YHWH's covenant people.</p>",
"25": "<p><b>Vahivdaltem bein habehemah hatehorah letemeah</b>: you shall therefore separate (<em>havdil</em>) the clean from the unclean beast and between unclean and clean birds. The <em>havdalah</em> (separation, distinction) that structures the purity laws is the same cognitive and ethical act demanded in all of Leviticus: maintaining the distinctions that YHWH established at creation. <em>Velo tesha'qetzu et-nafshoteichem</em>: you shall not defile yourselves through the animals. The connection between dietary separation and holiness-separation is explicit here.</p>",
"26": "<p><b>Vihyitem li qedoshim ki qadosh ani YHWH veavdil etchem min-haamim lihyot li</b>: you shall be holy to me, for I YHWH am holy, and I have separated you from the peoples to be mine. The holiness refrain reaches its fullest expression here: the source of the command (YHWH's holiness), the content (separation from the nations), and the purpose (to belong to YHWH) are all stated together. The closing verse of the penalty chapter's theological section presents holiness as both inherited (YHWH's character) and achieved (Israel's calling).</p>",
"27": "<p><b>Ve-ish o isha ki yihyeh bahem ov o yideoni mot yumatu</b>: a man or woman who is a medium (<em>ov</em>) or wizard (<em>yideoni</em>) shall be put to death — stoned, their blood is upon them. The chapter ends with the execution penalty for the two main forms of occult practice (cf. 19:31), bracketing the chapter with the theme of unauthorized access to spiritual knowledge. The penalties for Molech worship (ch. 20 opening) and occult practice (ch. 20 closing) frame all the sexual and kinship prohibitions between them, suggesting that all three — child sacrifice, sexual violations, and necromancy — are expressions of the same fundamental rejection of YHWH's covenant order.</p>"
},
"21": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 21 addresses priestly holiness specifically — the higher standard required of those who serve at the altar and approach the divine presence. <b>El-hakkohanim benei Aharon</b>: to the priests, the sons of Aaron. The priesthood has additional restrictions beyond those of ordinary Israelites, proportional to their proximity to the holy. The principle is consistent throughout Leviticus: the closer to the divine presence, the stricter the purity requirements.</p>",
"2": "<p><b>Ki im-lisheero haqarov alav</b>: except for his nearest kin — mother, father, son, daughter, brother. Priests may defile themselves (<em>yitamma</em> = become ritually impure) for these immediate family members by handling their corpses. The permitted exceptions define the irreducible family circle within which even priestly purity requirements yield to the obligations of family love and burial duty. The restriction to immediate relatives makes the list of exceptions minimal and precise.</p>",
"3": "<p><b>Ulechistoh habetulah haqerovah elaiv asher lo hayta leish lah yittamma</b>: for his sister, a virgin who is near to him and has had no husband, he may become unclean. The unmarried sister (still in the paternal household, not transferred to another family unit) counts among the immediate family for whom a priest may defile himself. The married sister, having joined another household, is no longer counted — a reflection of the patrilineal household structure where marriage transferred a woman's primary familial identity.</p>",
"4": "<p><b>Lo yitamma ba'al beammav lechallelo</b>: he shall not defile himself as a husband among his people, so as to profane himself. This verse is much disputed — it may refer to an in-law relationship or to a general prohibition against the priest defiling himself for more distant kin beyond the immediate family list.</p>",
"5": "<p><b>Lo yiqrechu qorcha beroshom ufe'at zeqanam lo yegallechu</b>: they shall not make bald patches on their heads or shave off the edges of their beards or make cuts (<em>seret</em>) on their flesh. The three prohibited mourning practices (head-shaving, beard-trimming, cutting the body) that were prohibited for all Israelites in 19:27-28 are here specifically prohibited for priests. The priest's body must remain unmarked — whole and undamaged — as befits one who represents the wholeness of the covenant community before YHWH.</p>",
"6": "<p><b>Qedoshim yihyu leiloheichem velo yechalelu shem eloheihem</b>: they shall be holy to their God and not profane the name of their God. The priest's holiness is specifically connected to the divine name: the priest's actions directly reflect on YHWH's name in a way that ordinary Israelites' actions do not. The priest mediates between the community and God — any defilement of the priest is a profanation of the divine name because the priest represents YHWH to the people and the people to YHWH.</p>",
"7": "<p><b>Isha zonah vachalala lo yiqachu</b>: they shall not marry a prostitute (<em>zonah</em>) or a woman who has been defiled (<em>chalala</em> = profaned/desecrated, a woman who has lost her ritual-purity status) or a woman divorced from her husband. The marriage restrictions for priests reflect the requirement that the priestly household be free from anything that carries the connotations of defilement or social dishonor. <em>Chalala</em> (the profaned/desecrated woman) is the feminine form of <em>chillel</em> (to profane) — a woman excluded from priestly circles.</p>",
"8": "<p><b>Veqiddashto ki et-lechem elohecha hu maqriv</b>: you shall sanctify (<em>qiddashto</em>) him, for he offers the bread of your God. The entire community has a stake in priestly holiness: <em>veqiddashto</em> is addressed to Israel collectively. The priestly holiness belongs not to the individual priest alone but to the community that depends on his mediation. YHWH himself is the sanctifier: <em>ki qadosh ani YHWH meqaddishchem</em> (for holy am I, YHWH who sanctifies you).</p>",
"9": "<p><b>Uvat ish kohen ki techel liznot</b>: and the daughter of a priest, if she profanes herself by whoring (<em>liznot</em>). She shall be burned with fire (<em>va-esh tisref</em>) — the most severe penalty in the chapter. The priest's daughter represents the priestly household's honor in a way that ordinary Israelites' daughters do not. Her sexual misconduct profanes her father: <em>et-aviha hi mechalelet</em>. The burning penalty (also in 20:14) is reserved for the most serious cases in the Holiness Code.</p>",
"10": "<p><b>Vehakohen haggadol me-echav asher-yutzaq al-rosho shemen hamishcha</b>: the high priest (<em>kohen haggadol</em>, literally the great priest) — upon whose head the anointing oil (<em>shemen hamishcha</em>) has been poured and who has been consecrated to wear the garments. The high priest bears the highest standard of holiness. He shall not uncover his head (<em>lo yifra rosho</em>) or tear his garments (<em>bigadav lo yifrom</em>) — the two standard mourning actions that even ordinary priests are restricted in performing. The high priest is completely prohibited from both.</p>",
"11": "<p><b>Veal kol-nafshot met lo yavo</b>: he shall not go near any dead body at all. The high priest may not defile himself even for his own father or mother — the strictest possible application of the proximity-holiness principle. The high priest's ongoing ritual purity is so essential to the functioning of the sanctuary (especially on Yom Kippur) that personal bereavement cannot be allowed to disqualify him. This creates an extraordinary human cost: the high priest must refrain from burying his own parents.</p>",
"12": "<p><b>Umin-hamiqddash lo yetze velo yechalel et-miqdash elohav</b>: he shall not leave the sanctuary (<em>hamiqddash</em>) or profane the sanctuary of his God. The high priest may not leave to attend a funeral even outside the sanctuary precincts. The reason: <em>ki nezer shemen mishchat elohav alav</em> (for the consecration of the anointing oil of his God is upon him). <em>Nezer</em> (consecration, crown — also the crown/diadem of the high priest's turban, Lev 8:9) describes the high priest's permanent state of consecration: the anointing oil that marks him as set apart cannot be temporarily set aside for personal mourning.</p>",
"13": "<p><b>Vehu isha bivtuleiha yiqqach</b>: he shall take a wife in her virginity (<em>bivtuleiha</em>). The high priest's wife must be a virgin (<em>betulah</em>) — an additional restriction beyond the ordinary priest's marriage rules (v7). The requirement of a virgin wife for the high priest reflects the highest level of the purity-and-wholeness principle: the high priest's household must be free from any previous sexual relationship that might carry the associations of mixed loyalty or prior covenant.</p>",
"14": "<p><b>Almana ugerushah vechalala zonah et-eleh lo yiqqach</b>: a widow, a divorced woman, a desecrated woman, a prostitute — these he shall not marry. The list for the high priest is more extensive than for ordinary priests (v7): widows are also excluded (ordinary priests may marry widows). Only <em>betulat amav</em> (a virgin from his own people) is permitted. The restriction to a virgin from his own people preserves the high priest's household as a symbol of unbroken covenant fidelity.</p>",
"15": "<p><b>Velo yechalel zaro beammav</b>: he shall not profane his offspring among his people. The high priest's marriage restrictions are motivated by dynastic as well as personal holiness: the priestly line must be maintained in an unambiguous state of holiness. <em>Ki ani YHWH meqaddisho</em>: for I am YHWH who sanctifies him — YHWH himself is the source of the high priest's sanctification, which the marriage rules protect and maintain.</p>",
"16": "<p>YHWH speaks to Moses to deliver the physical-defect regulations for priests who cannot offer the bread of God at the altar.</p>",
"17": "<p><b>Ish min-zaracha ledorotam asher yihyeh vo mum lo yiqrav lehaqriv lechem elohav</b>: any man of Aaron's descendants throughout their generations who has a defect (<em>mum</em>) may not approach to offer the bread of his God. <em>Mum</em> (defect, blemish, spot) is the same word used for the unblemished quality required of sacrificial animals. The principle of correspondence: as the offering must be without defect, so must the offerer. The priest represents the perfection of what human beings are called to be before God — physical wholeness symbolizes the spiritual and moral integrity required for covenant mediation.</p>",
"18": "<p>The list of disqualifying defects: <b>iver</b> (blind), <b>pisseach</b> (lame), <b>charum</b> (mutilated face/nose — or with a defect of the nose, debated), <b>sarua</b> (a limb too long), <b>shever regel</b> (broken foot), <b>shever yad</b> (broken hand).</p>",
"19": "<p><b>Gibbein o daq</b>: hunchbacked (<em>gibbein</em>) or dwarfed (<em>daq</em>). The list continues with conditions affecting posture and stature. <b>Tevalul beeino</b>: defect in his eye — perhaps a cataract or other visual impairment beyond full blindness. <b>Garav</b>: itch/scurvy. <b>Yalefet</b>: scabs. <b>Merua ashech</b>: crushed testicle — the final item in the list covers damage to the reproductive system.</p>",
"20": "<p>This verse continues listing the defects (including crushed testicle) from v19. The comprehensive list demonstrates that the restriction covers all categories of physical imperfection — not as a moral judgment but as a symbolic system: those who represent the covenant community before a holy God must embody the completeness and wholeness that the covenant life is designed to produce.</p>",
"21": "<p><b>Kol-ish asher-bo mum mizera Aharon hakohen lo yiggash lehaqriv et-ishei YHWH</b>: any man of Aaron's descendants who has a defect shall not approach to offer the fire offerings of YHWH. The prohibiton is absolute for altar service, but qualified in the next verse: the defective priest may still eat the sacred food.</p>",
"22": "<p><b>Lechem elohav miqodshei haqodashim umin-haqodashim yochal</b>: he may eat the bread of his God, both of the most holy things and of the holy things. The defective priest retains his status as priest and his right to eat the sacred food; he is only prohibited from active altar service. The distinction preserves his dignity and his covenant standing while maintaining the integrity of the altar service. The defect affects what he may do, not who he is.</p>",
"23": "<p><b>Ach el-happarochet lo yavo ve-el-hamizbeach lo yiggash</b>: but he shall not go through the veil (<em>parochet</em>) or approach the altar. The two most sacred locations — the veil separating the holy of holies and the altar of burnt offering — are specifically prohibited to the defective priest. His access to the holiest spaces is restricted even though his priesthood continues. The spatial restriction mirrors the graduated holiness structure of the entire sanctuary complex.</p>",
"24": "<p><b>Vayedaber Moshe el-Aharon veel-banav veel-kol-benei Yisrael</b>: Moses spoke to Aaron and to his sons and to all the people of Israel. The priestly holiness laws of ch. 21 are communicated to the whole people — not kept as arcane priestly knowledge but made public. The community's understanding of priestly standards matters because the community depends on and has a stake in the integrity of its mediators. The chapter closes with the widest possible audience for the priestly holiness code.</p>"
}
}

